  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "FJ+i++uOs6TpuaYO0PCJp3CRA6w=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nEvery postage stamp batch has a fixed structure of **65,536 buckets (2^16)** into which chunks are distributed by the first 16 bits of their address, producing non-uniform effective capacity.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Bucket depth is fixed at 16 regardless of batch depth\n- Each bucket holds `2^(depth - 16)` slots\n- Chunks assigned to buckets by the first 16 bits of their chunk address\n- **Immutable batches** fail once ANY single bucket fills up \u2014 random distribution yields only ~62-87% effective utilization depending on batch depth\n- **Mutable batches** never exhaust \u2014 when a bucket overflows, the oldest chunk in that bucket is replaced (ideal for feeds)\n\n## Effective utilization table (99.9% confidence)\n\n| Depth | Effective capacity | Utilization |\n|------:|-------------------:|------------:|\n| 20    | ~680 MB            | ~62.89%     |\n| 22    | ~7.7 GB            | ~65.05%     |\n| 24    | ~43 GB             | ~68.48%     |\n| 28    | ~909 GB            | ~87%+       |\n\n## Why it matters\n\nPricing by nominal `2^depth * amount` dramatically overestimates usable capacity on shallow batches. Users should size up or use `GET /stamps/{id}/buckets` to monitor hot-bucket exhaustion.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
    }
  },
